Start in a plank position with hands under shoulders. Lower your body by bending arms, then push back up, engaging chest, shoulders, and triceps.

Start by lying face down on the floor. Lift your body off the ground using your toes and forearms, keeping your body in a straight line from head to heels. Support your upper body with your forearms and elbows, and engage your Core to hold the position.

Begin in a standing position, then squat down and place your hands on the ground. Kick your feet back into a plank position, perform a push-up, and jump your feet back to the squat position. Explode upward into a jump. Burpees provide a full-body workout and cardiovascular challenge.
Walk, jog, or run on a motorized device or in place. Adjust speed and incline for intensity variation. A versatile cardio exercise.
Hang from a pull-up bar with your hands shoulder-width apart, palms facing away. Pull your body up until your chin is above the bar, engaging your back and arms.
Start with a manageable pace and gradually increase your speed and repetitions as your fitness level improves.

Sit or stand with a straight spine, holding dumbbells at shoulder height with palms facing your body. Rotate your palms outward as you press the dumbbells overhead, then reverse the motion on the way down.
Stand with dumbbells in each hand, palms facing forward. Curl the weights toward your shoulders, engaging the biceps. Lower them back down with control.
Sit or stand, hold dumbbells at shoulder height, and press upward. Lower with control. Engage Core for stability.
Stand with your feet hip-width apart, bend at the hips and knees to grasp the barbell with an overhand grip. Pull the barbell toward your lower ribs, engaging your back and biceps.
Sit facing the machine, grab the bar or attachment, and pull it down to chest level, engaging the lats. Control the upward movement.
Stand with dumbbells in hand, arms by sides. Lift arms sideways to shoulder level, keeping a slight bend in the elbows. Lower with control.
Hang from a pull-up bar or use parallel bars. Lift your legs as high as possible while keeping them straight. Lower them back down to engage the lower Core and hip flexors.
Grip the parallel bars with your arms extended. Lower your body by bending your elbows, then push back up. Tricep dips engage your triceps, shoulders, and chest.
Bend your upper body forward with a flat back, holding a dumbbell in each hand. Extend your arms backward, focusing on the triceps. Bend your elbows and repeat.
Lie on a bench, grip the bar with hands closer than shoulder-width. Lower to the chest and press back up. Engage Core for stability.
Hang from the pull-up bar with a supinated grip (palms facing you). Pull your body up until your chin is above the bar. Lower yourself back down.
Sit on the floor with your knees bent, lean back slightly, and lift your feet off the ground. Hold a weighted object and twist your torso to one side, then to the other, engaging your Core and Core.

Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, holding a barbell or dumbbells with palms facing down. Keeping your upper arms stationary, curl the weight upward by contracting your forearms. Lower the weight back down with control.
Lie on a flat bench, hold weights at chest level, and press upward. Control the descent. Engage Core for stability.
Stand with a dumbbell in each hand, palms facing your torso (neutral grip). Keep your upper arms stationary and curl the weights toward your shoulders using only your forearms.
Lie on a bench with your feet flat on the floor. Lift the barbell off the rack, lower it to your chest, and push it back up. Engage your chest, shoulders, and triceps.

Stand with feet hip-width apart, bend at the hips, and knees to grasp the barbell. Lift the bar by extending your hips and knees, keeping your back straight and chest up. Lower the bar back to the ground, engaging the lower back, glutes, hamstrings, quads, and Core.
Start in a push-up position with your arms fully extended. Alternate bringing your knees toward your chest in a running motion while keeping your Core engaged.

Lie on your back with knees bent and feet flat on the floor. Cross your arms over your chest or place them behind your head. Engage your Core and lift your upper body off the ground by flexing your spine.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart. Bend at the knees and hips, lowering your body while keeping your back straight, then push back up. Engage the quadriceps, hamstrings, glutes, lower back, and Core.
Stand with your feet together. Take a step forward with one leg, bend both knees to lower your body, then push back up. Engage your quadriceps, hamstrings, glutes, and calves.
Stand with your back against a wall and slide down until your knees are at a 90-degree angle. Hold this position, engaging your leg muscles. Wall sits are an isometric exercise for leg endurance.
Lie on your back, lift head and shoulders, tap heels while twisting. Engage Core. Control the twist. If doing it correctly, you may look like a Penguin.
Lie on your back with knees bent. Lift your head and shoulders off the ground. Reach forward to touch your ankles, engaging your Core and Core.

Lie on your back with knees bent. Perform a traditional crunch by lifting your upper body off the ground. Simultaneously, extend your arms forward in a punching motion, engaging both the Core and upper body.
Lie on an incline bench, hold dumbbells above chest, and press upward. Lower weights with control. Engage Core for stability.
Stand or sit, hold weight overhead with both hands, and lower it behind the head by bending at the elbows. Extend arms upward.
Kneel on a preacher bench, allowing your arms to hang straight down. Curl the barbell or EZ bar toward your face, targeting the biceps.
Place hands on an inclined surface, keeping body in a plank position. Lower your chest toward the surface, then push back up, engaging chest, shoulders, triceps, and Core.
Place feet on a decline surface, hands on the ground in a plank position. Lower your chest toward the ground, then push back up, engaging chest, shoulders, triceps, and Core.
Get in a plank position with hands close together, forming a diamond shape with your thumbs and index fingers. Lower your chest, then push back up, engaging chest, shoulders, triceps, and Core.
Start in a lunge position with one foot forward and the other foot extended behind. Jump explosively, switching the positions of your legs mid-air. Land softly and immediately go into the next jump.
Sit on an incline bench, arms hanging straight down, and curl the dumbbells upward, keeping your upper arms stationary. Engage your biceps.
Lie on your back with legs straight. Lift your legs off the ground a few inches and cross them in a scissor-like motion, engaging your Core and hip flexors.

Start in a push-up position with one hand placed wider than shoulder-width, and the other hand closer to your body. Lower your chest to one side, then push back up, engaging chest, shoulders, triceps, and Core. Alternate sides in each repetition.
Start in a plank position. Lower your body in a pushup, then explosively push off the ground, lifting your hands off the floor. Engage chest, shoulders, triceps, and Core.
Start in a plank position. Place your hands close together with palms facing towards you. Lower your chest to the ground, then push back up, engaging chest, shoulders, triceps, and Core.

Start in a regular push-up position with hands under shoulders. Lower your chest to the ground, then move one hand closer to the center of your chest while the other hand moves wider. Push back up, engaging chest, shoulders, triceps, and Core. Alternate hands in each repetition.
Begin in a downward dog yoga pose, with hips in the air and hands on the ground. Lower your head toward the ground, then push back up, engaging shoulders, upper chest, triceps, and Core.

Start in a push-up position with your hands crossed under your shoulders, one hand placed on the opposite side of your chest. Lower your body, then push back up, engaging chest, shoulders, triceps, and Core. Alternate hand positions in each repetition.

Start in a handstand position against a wall or in free space if advanced. Lower your body by bending your elbows, bringing your head toward the ground, then press back up to the starting handstand position.

Start in a standard pushup position. Lower your body to the ground and explosively push up, allowing your hands to leave the ground. Clap your hands together before catching yourself and returning to the starting position.
Begin in a standard pushup position. Lower your body deeper than a regular pushup, allowing your chest to almost touch the ground. Push back up to the starting position.
Start in a standing position, perform a squat, place hands on the ground, kick feet back into a plank, perform a pushup, jump feet back towards hands, and explosively jump up.
Lie on your side with legs straight. Support your upper body with your forearm. Lift your hips off the ground to create a straight line from head to heels, engaging Core and Core.

Sit on the floor with legs extended and place your hands behind you, fingers pointing toward your feet. Lift your hips off the ground to create a straight line from head to heels. Engage your Core, back, and shoulders.
Sit on the floor, legs extended. Hold a medicine ball, lean back, and lift your legs and upper body off the ground, forming a V shape. Engage your Core.

Lie on your back with knees bent. Lift your head and shoulders off the ground and twist your torso to touch your right hand to your left foot, then alternate to your left hand to your right foot, engaging the Core and Core.
Lie on your back with arms extended behind you and legs straight. Simultaneously lift your upper body and legs towards each other, forming a V-shape. Lower back down with control.

Lie on your back with knees bent and feet flat. Hold a medicine ball at chest level. Perform a sit-up, lifting your upper body towards your knees while holding the medicine ball. Lower back down with control.
Secure yourself in an inverted position. Perform a sit-up by lifting your upper body towards your knees while inverted. Engage your core and control the descent.

Lie on your back with your hands behind your head and legs lifted. Bring one knee toward your chest while twisting your torso to touch your opposite elbow to the knee. Alternate sides in a pedaling motion.

Lie on your back with knees bent and hands behind your head. Lift your upper body off the ground while simultaneously pushing your legs outward in a V-shape. Bring them back together as you lower your upper body.
Lie on an incline bench with your head higher than your feet. Place your hands behind your head, lift your upper body towards your knees, and contract your abdominal muscles.
Lie on your back with knees bent and hands behind your head. Perform a crunch, but twist your torso to bring your right elbow towards your left knee. Alternate sides.
Lie on your back with hands under your hips. Lift your legs a few inches off the ground and perform fluttering kicks, engaging lower Core and hip flexors.
Lie on your back with legs straight. Simultaneously lift your upper body and legs, reaching for your toes and creating a "V". Engage your Core, hip flexors, and lower back.
Lie on your back with knees bent and feet flat on the mat. Lift your hips towards the ceiling, extending one leg straight. Lower your hips and leg back down, then switch legs.
Stand with feet shoulder-width apart. Place one hand on your hip and slowly lean to the side, bringing the opposite hand down towards your knee. Return to the starting position and switch sides.
Lie on your side with your elbow directly beneath your shoulder. Lift your hips, creating a straight line from head to heels. Hold the position, engaging your obliques. Switch sides.
Start in a side plank position with your elbow directly beneath your shoulder. Rotate your torso, bringing your top arm down towards the mat. Return to the side plank position and switch sides.

Stand with the barbell or dumbbells in front of your thighs. Hinge at the hips, lowering the weight while keeping your back straight, and then return to the starting position. Engage hamstrings, glutes, and lower back.

Stand with feet wider than shoulder-width apart. Shift your weight to one side, bending that knee while keeping the other leg straight. Return to the center and repeat on the opposite side to engage quads, hamstrings, and inner and outer thighs.
Stand with dumbbells in each hand, palms facing your body. Curl one dumbbell across your chest toward the opposite shoulder, alternating sides. Engage biceps.
Start with one foot forward and one foot back. Jump explosively, switching the position of your feet mid-air, and land with the opposite foot forward. Engage leg muscles for a plyometric exercise.

Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, holding a kettlebell with both hands in front of you. Swing the kettlebell between your legs, then thrust your hips forward to swing it up to chest level. Engage glutes, hamstrings, lower back, Core, and shoulders.
Stand with feet shoulder-width apart. Jump repeatedly by pushing off your toes while keeping your legs straight, engaging calf muscles and legs.
Sit on a bench with back support, holding a barbell or dumbbells at shoulder height. Push the weight upward until your arms are fully extended. Engage your shoulders and triceps.

Stand in front of the box with feet shoulder-width apart. Jump onto the box with both feet, extending your hips and knees. Step back down and repeat. Box jumps are a plyometric exercise for leg strength and power.
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, bend at the hips, and grasp the barbell or dumbbells with an overhand grip. Pull the weights toward your lower ribs, engaging your back and biceps.
Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, hold the barbell or dumbbells at shoulder height. Bend your knees slightly, then explosively push the weight overhead. Engage your shoulders and triceps.

Lie on your back with a kettlebell in one hand. Perform a series of movements, including rolling, bridging, and kneeling, to stand up while keeping the kettlebell overhead. Reverse the movements to return to the starting position.
Lie on your back with your knees bent and feet flat on the ground. Lift your hips off the ground by squeezing your glutes, creating a straight line from shoulders to knees. Lower and repeat.
Stand with your feet hip-width apart. Rise onto your toes by lifting your heels as high as possible. Lower your heels back down to work your calf muscles.

Stand with your feet wider than shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell or kettlebell in each hand. Take small, controlled steps side to side while keeping your posture upright. This exercise targets the inner thighs and glutes.
Hold the handles or a parallel bar with a neutral grip (palms facing each other). Hang with arms extended, then pull your body up until your chin is above the bar. Lower yourself back down.
Hang from the pull-up bar with your arms fully extended. Initiate the movement by retracting your shoulder blades without bending your arms. Lower your body back down.

Stand on an elevated surface to reach the pull-up bar. Grasp the bar with a supinated grip (palms facing you) and jump or step up to the top position of the pull-up. Lower your body slowly and in a controlled manner.
Stand upright with feet hip-width apart. Lift one knee toward your chest while balancing on the other leg. Alternate legs in a marching motion, engaging your core throughout.

Stand with feet shoulder-width apart. Grip the barbell (or dumbbells) with hands slightly wider than shoulder-width, palms facing forward. Lift the weight from behind your neck to an overhead position, then lower it back down.

Stand with feet shoulder-width apart. Hold dumbbells in front of your thighs or grip a barbell with an overhand grip. Lift the weights directly in front of you until your arms are parallel to the ground, then lower them back down.

Stand with feet hip-width apart. Hold the barbell at shoulder height with an overhand grip or hold dumbbells at shoulder level. Press the weight directly overhead until your arms are fully extended, then lower it back down.
Sit or stand with a straight spine. Hold dumbbells at shoulder height or a barbell at chest level. Press the weights directly overhead until your arms are fully extended, then lower them back down.
Start in a downward dog yoga position, forming an inverted V with your body. Lower your head towards the ground by bending your elbows, then press back up to the starting position.

Lie on your back on a bench or the floor. Hold a barbell or dumbbells with arms fully extended above your chest. Bend your elbows, lowering the weight toward your forehead, then extend back to the starting position.
Sit on the edge of a bench, gripping the edge with hands shoulder-width apart. Slide your hips off the bench and lower your body by bending your elbows, then push back up to the starting position.

Stand with a slight bend in your knees, hinge at your hips, and lean forward. Hold a dumbbell in each hand, extend your arms straight back, and squeeze your triceps at the top. Lower the weights back down.

Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, holding the barbell in front of your thighs with palms facing your body. Keeping the bar close to your body, curl it up to your upper chest, squeezing the biceps at the top, and then lower it back down.

Lie face down on a bench with your chest at the edge, holding a barbell or using a Smith machine. Grab the bar with a wide grip, arms fully extended. Pull the bar up to your chest, then lower it back down.

Lie on a bench or across a stable surface with only your upper back and shoulders supported. Hold a dumbbell or barbell with both hands above your chest. Lower the weight backward in a controlled manner, allowing your arms to stretch, then bring it back to the starting position.

Hang from a pull-up bar with an overhand grip, hands wider than shoulder-width apart. Perform a pullup, but as you ascend, shift your body to one side, extending the opposite arm straight. This creates a dynamic, archer-like movement.

Lie on a decline bench, holding a dumbbell in each hand with palms facing each other. Extend your arms outward, maintaining a slight bend in the elbows, then bring the weights back up to the starting position.
Stand with feet together. Step to the side with one foot, bending the knee and pushing your hips back. Keep the other leg straight. Return to the starting position and repeat on the other side.
Stand with feet hip-width apart. Step one foot backward, lowering your body until both knees are bent at a 90-degree angle. Push through the front heel to return to the starting position.

Start standing with feet together. Take a step forward with one foot, lowering your body until both knees are bent at a 90-degree angle. Push through the front heel and bring the back foot forward, alternating legs as you walk.
Position the safety squat bar across your shoulders or use a Smith machine. Stand with feet shoulder-width apart. Squat down by bending at the knees and hips, keeping your back straight.
Stand with the step platform in front of you. Step onto the platform with one foot, then bring the other foot up to meet it. Perform a squat, lowering your body by bending at the knees and hips.
Stand with feet shoulder-width apart. Place a barbell across your upper back or hold your hands behind your head. Hinge at the hips, leaning forward while keeping a straight back.
Lie face down, grip the handles or bar, and pull toward your chest. Keep your chest in contact with the support, focusing on the upper back and chest.
Sit at the cable row machine, using the wide grip attachment, and pull the handle toward your chest. Focus on engaging your upper back, mid-back, and chest.
Stand facing the cable machine, grip the bar with straight arms, and push it down towards your thighs, engaging your lats and triceps.
Sit on the machine, adjust arms to chest level, and push them together in a fly motion. Control the return.
Sit on the leg extension machine, hook your ankles under the padded bar, and extend your legs upward, engaging your quadriceps.
Lie face down on the leg curl machine, secure your ankles under the padded bar, and curl your legs toward your glutes, engaging the hamstrings.
Sit on the leg press machine, place your feet on the platform, and press it upward to extend your legs. Engage your quadriceps, hamstrings, and glutes.
Stand on the hack squat machine with your shoulders under the shoulder pads. Lower your body by bending at the knees, then push back up to engage your quadriceps, hamstrings, and glutes.
Sit on the edge of the parallel bars with your hands placed shoulder-width apart. Lower your body by bending your elbows, then push back up to engage the triceps, chest, and shoulders.
Lie face down on the leg curl machine, hooking your ankles under the padded lever. Curl your legs upward, engaging your hamstrings and calves, and then lower them back down.
Sit at a preacher curl bench, placing your upper arms on the pad. Grasp the barbell or dumbbells with an underhand grip. Curl the weights upward to work the biceps.

Face away from the anchor point of the suspension trainer, holding the handles with an overhand grip. Walk your feet forward, leaning your body forward. Bend your elbows, lowering your body toward the ground, then extend your arms to return to the starting position.

Face the anchor point of the suspension trainer, grab the handles with palms facing up, and lean back. Pull your body up toward the handles, bringing your hands close to your temples, then extend your arms back down.

Set up a suspension trainer or use a bar at hip height. Lie underneath, holding the handles or bar with an overhand grip. Keep your body straight and pull your chest up toward the handles or bar, then lower yourself back down.
Stand inside the trap bar with feet hip-width apart. Grasp the handles, keep your chest up, and squat down by bending at the knees and hips. Maintain a neutral spine.

Stand with feet hip-width apart, securing your ankles against the pad of a sissy squat bench or using a Smith machine. Lean back, allowing your knees to bend, and lower your body by bending at the knees.

Kneel on the glute ham raise bench with your feet secured. Lower your upper body forward while keeping your back straight. Use your hamstrings and glutes to lift your torso back to the starting position.
